    <h2>Types of Cotton Candy Machines in India</h2>
    <p>Cotton candy machines (also called candy floss machines) work by heating sugar in a spinning head. The centrifugal force pushes melted sugar through tiny holes, creating thin strands that cool instantly and are collected on a stick or cone by the operator. Here are the main types available in the Indian market.</p>

    <h3>1. Manual/Semi-Automatic Electric Cotton Candy Machine</h3>
    <p>This is the most common type used by street vendors and event operators across India. The machine has a large round bowl (typically 50–70 cm diameter), a central spinning head with a heating element, and a simple on/off switch. The operator adds sugar to the spinning head, waits for strands to form, and manually collects them onto a stick.</p>

    <p><strong>Key specifications:</strong></p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Bowl diameter:</strong> 50–70 cm (larger bowl = easier collection)</li>
      <li><strong>Power:</strong> 500–1500W</li>
      <li><strong>Output:</strong> 1–3 sticks per minute (40–80 sticks per hour for a skilled operator)</li>
      <li><strong>Sugar consumption:</strong> 20–30g of sugar per stick</li>
      <li><strong>Spinning head material:</strong> Aluminium or stainless steel</li>
    </ul>

    <p><strong>Price range:</strong> ₹4,000 – ₹18,000 depending on size, build quality, and brand. Budget models from local manufacturers start at ₹4,000–₹6,000, while quality commercial units from established brands cost ₹10,000–₹18,000.</p>

    <p><strong>Ideal for:</strong> Street vendors, event caterers, school fairs, birthday party businesses, small stalls, and anyone starting a cotton candy business in India on a budget.</p>

    <h3>2. Gas-Operated Cotton Candy Machine</h3>
    <p>Gas cotton candy machines replace the electric heating element with an LPG gas burner. They are preferred by operators who work in outdoor settings, rural areas, or locations with unreliable power supply. The gas flame heats the spinning head faster and more consistently than entry-level electric models.</p>

    <p><strong>Key specifications:</strong></p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Bowl diameter:</strong> 55–75 cm</li>
      <li><strong>Gas consumption:</strong> 100–200g LPG per hour</li>
      <li><strong>Output:</strong> 60–120 sticks per hour</li>
      <li><strong>Spinning mechanism:</strong> Motor-driven (requires minimal electricity for the motor, or battery-operated)</li>
    </ul>

    <p><strong>Price range:</strong> ₹15,000 – ₹30,000. Gas models cost more upfront than basic electric models but offer faster heat-up, higher output, and independence from the electricity grid.</p>

    <p><strong>Ideal for:</strong> Outdoor events, carnivals, melas, rural fairs, and mobile cotton candy businesses. If you're building a mobile food business, also explore our <a href="/blog/sugarcane-juice-machine-india">sugarcane juice machine guide</a> for another high-margin addition to your cart.</p>

    <h3>3. Fully Automatic Cotton Candy Machine</h3>
    <p>Automatic cotton candy machines handle the entire process — from sugar feeding to strand formation to collection — with minimal operator intervention. Some advanced models even package the cotton candy into bags or containers automatically. These are used by large-scale operations, amusement parks, and cotton candy brands that supply to retail stores.</p>

    <p><strong>Key specifications:</strong></p>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>Output:</strong> 100–200+ sticks per hour (or 5–10+ kg of cotton candy per hour)</li>
      <li><strong>Power:</strong> 2000–3000W (three-phase for industrial models)</li>
      <li><strong>Automation level:</strong> Sugar auto-feed, automatic collection, some with packaging</li>
      <li><strong>Footprint:</strong> Larger than manual models — typically requires a dedicated counter space</li>
    </ul>

    <p><strong>Price range:</strong> ₹35,000 – ₹80,000. Fully imported automatic machines from Chinese or Japanese manufacturers can cost ₹1,00,000+.</p>

    <p><strong>Ideal for:</strong> Amusement parks, cinema chains, cotton candy brands, event management companies, and any business where high, consistent output is required with minimal labour.</p>

