    <h2>FSSAI and Licensing Requirements</h2>
    <p>Operating a popcorn or cotton candy business in India requires specific licences and registrations. Here's what you need:</p>

    <h3>Mandatory Licences</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>FSSAI Registration (Basic):</strong> Required for all food businesses with annual turnover up to ₹12 lakh. Costs ₹100 per year (government fee) + ₹500–₹2,000 if you use an agent. Valid for 1–5 years. This is sufficient for small stalls and mobile carts.</li>
      <li><strong>FSSAI State Licence:</strong> Required if annual turnover exceeds ₹12 lakh. Costs ₹2,000–₹5,000 per year. Needed for cinema chains, mall outlets, and larger operations.</li>
      <li><strong>GST Registration:</strong> Required if annual turnover exceeds ₹20 lakh (₹10 lakh for special category states). Most small stalls can operate without GST registration initially.</li>
      <li><strong>Shop and Establishment Licence:</strong> Required for fixed shops. Issued by the local municipal corporation. Costs vary by city (typically ₹1,000–₹5,000).</li>
      <li><strong>Street Vendor Certificate:</strong> For mobile cart operators. Issued under the Street Vendors Act, 2014. Available through local municipal authorities.</li>
    </ul>

    <p>For a comprehensive guide on food business licensing, including step-by-step application instructions and costs, read our detailed <a href="/blog/fssai-license-cost-registration-india">FSSAI licence cost and registration guide</a>.</p>

    <h3>Hygiene and Safety Requirements</h3>
    <ul>
      <li>All food-contact surfaces must be food-grade stainless steel (SS 304) or food-safe materials</li>
      <li>Operators must wear gloves and head coverings when handling food</li>
      <li>Raw materials (kernels, sugar, oil) must be stored in airtight, labelled containers</li>
      <li>Gas cylinder installations must comply with BIS standards and have a valid pressure test certificate</li>
      <li>Fire extinguisher required for gas-operated setups</li>
    </ul>

    <h2>Maintenance and Cleaning</h2>
    <p>Regular maintenance extends the life of your popcorn and cotton candy machine, ensures consistent output quality, and prevents costly breakdowns. Here's a maintenance schedule for both machine types.</p>

    <h3>Popcorn Machine Maintenance</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>After every use:</strong> Wipe down the kettle with a damp cloth while still warm. Clean glass panels inside and out. Empty the crumb tray. Remove any burnt kernels from the kettle.</li>
      <li><strong>Weekly:</strong> Deep clean the kettle with warm soapy water. Inspect heating elements for carbon buildup. Check electrical connections and wiring for wear.</li>
      <li><strong>Monthly:</strong> Lubricate any moving parts (stirring mechanism, kettle hinge). Inspect and clean the heat lamp. Check gas connections and hoses (for gas models).</li>
      <li><strong>Every 6 months:</strong> Professional inspection of electrical components. Replace worn gaskets or seals. Check gas regulator condition.</li>
      <li><strong>Common spare parts:</strong> Heating element (₹500–₹2,000), kettle gasket (₹200–₹500), heat lamp bulb (₹100–₹300), stirring motor (₹1,000–₹3,000).</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Cotton Candy Machine Maintenance</h3>
    <ul>
      <li><strong>After every use:</strong> Remove the spinning head and soak in warm water for 15–20 minutes to dissolve sugar residue. Wipe down the bowl. Clean the outer rim where sugar strands accumulate.</li>
      <li><strong>Weekly:</strong> Deep clean the spinning head — ensure all tiny holes are clear of crystallised sugar (use a thin wire or needle). Inspect the heating element. Clean the motor housing.</li>
      <li><strong>Monthly:</strong> Lubricate the motor bearing. Check belt tension (for belt-driven models). Inspect electrical connections.</li>
      <li><strong>Common spare parts:</strong> Spinning head/ribbon (₹800–₹2,500), heating element (₹400–₹1,500), motor belt (₹200–₹500), carbon brushes (₹150–₹400).</li>
    </ul>

