    <h2>Common Mistakes When Buying Popcorn and Cotton Candy Machines</h2>
    <p>Based on feedback from hundreds of food business owners across India, here are the most frequent mistakes buyers make — and how to avoid them.</p>

    <ol>
      <li><strong>Buying the cheapest machine available:</strong> Ultra-budget machines (under ₹5,000 for popcorn, under ₹4,000 for cotton candy) are almost always made from inferior materials with weak heating elements. They fail within 2–3 months of commercial use. Invest in a quality commercial-grade machine — it costs more upfront but saves you replacement costs and downtime.</li>
      <li><strong>Ignoring the material grade:</strong> Always insist on SS 304 stainless steel for all food-contact parts. Lower-grade steel rusts quickly and is not food-safe. The price difference is typically only 15–25% more, but the machine lasts 3–5x longer.</li>
      <li><strong>Overestimating your initial volume:</strong> Start with a machine sized for your realistic day-one volume, not your dream volume. You can always upgrade later. Buying an industrial machine for a small stall wastes money and space.</li>
      <li><strong>Not checking warranty and after-sales service:</strong> Always buy from a brand or dealer that offers at least a 6-month warranty and has local service capability. A cheap machine from an unknown brand with no service support is a costly gamble.</li>
      <li><strong>Forgetting operating costs:</strong> The machine price is just the beginning. Factor in electricity/gas costs, raw materials, packaging, rent, and labour when calculating your total business cost. Read our <a href="/blog/how-to-buy-bakery-equipment">equipment buying guide</a> for a complete checklist applicable to any food equipment purchase.</li>
      <li><strong>Skipping FSSAI registration:</strong> Operating without FSSAI registration exposes you to fines of ₹5 lakh or more. Basic registration costs only ₹100/year — there's no excuse to skip it.</li>
      <li><strong>Not tasting samples before buying:</strong> Ask the dealer for a live demonstration. The quality of popcorn or cotton candy produced by different machines varies significantly. A demonstration reveals issues like uneven heating, slow output, or poor sugar spinning that specs alone won't show.</li>
      <li><strong>Ignoring the local electrical supply:</strong> If your location has single-phase power (most homes and small shops), don't buy a three-phase machine. Conversely, if you have three-phase power, you can access more powerful and efficient equipment. Check your power supply before ordering.</li>
    </ol>

