    <h2>Frequently Asked Questions (FAQ)</h2>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-q">What is the price of a commercial popcorn machine in India in 2026?</div>
      <div class="faq-a">Commercial popcorn machine prices in India range from ₹5,000 for a basic electric countertop model to ₹1,50,000+ for an industrial gas-operated machine with a cart and warming showcase. The most popular commercial option — a medium-sized electric countertop machine with a glass cabinet — costs between ₹12,000 and ₹25,000. Gas-operated models start at ₹15,000. Prices vary by brand, material grade (SS 304 vs mild steel), capacity, and whether the machine includes a cart or showcase. GST at 18% is typically extra on listed prices.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-q">What is the price of a cotton candy machine in India?</div>
      <div class="faq-a">Cotton candy machine prices in India start at ₹4,000 for a basic tabletop model suitable for home use or small parties. Commercial semi-automatic machines cost ₹8,000–₹18,000, gas-operated models range from ₹15,000–₹30,000, and fully automatic commercial cotton candy machines cost ₹35,000–₹80,000. For a standard commercial stall, a machine in the ₹10,000–₹20,000 range is the sweet spot — offering reliable output of 40–80 sticks per hour with minimal maintenance.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-q">Which is better — gas or electric popcorn machine?</div>
      <div class="faq-a">It depends on your location and use case. Electric popcorn machines are better for indoor use (cinemas, malls, shops) — they are cleaner, safer, easier to operate, and produce consistent results. Gas popcorn machines are better for outdoor stalls, events, and locations without reliable electricity — they offer higher output, lower operating costs per batch, and no dependency on the power grid. If you operate indoors with reliable power, go electric. If you need portability or work outdoors, go gas.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-q">How much profit can I make from a popcorn business in India?</div>
      <div class="faq-a">A commercial popcorn stall in India can generate a net profit of ₹35,000–₹50,000 per month selling 100 servings per day at ₹30 each. The raw material cost per serving is just ₹4–₹8 (kernels, oil, salt, packaging), giving you a gross margin of 65–90%. Cinema and mall popcorn operations earn even higher margins — a ₹200 tub of popcorn costs less than ₹15 in raw materials. The initial investment of ₹30,000–₹50,000 typically pays back within 1–2 months.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-q">How much profit can I make from a cotton candy business?</div>
      <div class="faq-a">Cotton candy has the highest profit margin of almost any food business — 75–92%. A stick of cotton candy costs ₹2–₹6 to make (sugar, colour, stick, bag) and sells for ₹10–₹30 at stalls or ₹30–₹80 at malls and events. A cotton candy stall operating 20 days a month selling 80 sticks per day can earn a net profit of ₹20,000–₹25,000. At events and carnivals with higher foot traffic, daily profits can reach ₹3,000–₹5,000 easily.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-q">Do I need an FSSAI licence to sell popcorn or cotton candy in India?</div>
      <div class="faq-a">Yes, FSSAI registration is mandatory for any food business in India, including popcorn and cotton candy stalls. For small businesses with annual turnover up to ₹12 lakh, FSSAI Basic Registration is sufficient — it costs just ₹100 per year (government fee). For larger operations exceeding ₹12 lakh turnover, you need an FSSAI State Licence costing ₹2,000–₹5,000 per year. You also need a street vendor certificate (for carts) or shop licence (for fixed locations). Read our complete <a href="/blog/fssai-license-cost-registration-india">FSSAI licence guide</a> for step-by-step instructions.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-q">What type of popcorn kernels should I use for a commercial machine?</div>
      <div class="faq-a">There are two main types of popcorn kernels: butterfly (snowflake) and mushroom. Butterfly kernels are irregular in shape with many "wings" — they are lighter, fluffier, and best for plain salted or butter popcorn. Mushroom kernels pop into a round, ball-like shape — they are sturdier and hold coatings better, making them ideal for caramel, cheese, and flavoured popcorn. For a standard commercial stall selling plain popcorn, use butterfly kernels (₹80–₹120/kg). For flavoured/gourmet popcorn, use mushroom kernels (₹100–₹150/kg). Buy in bulk (25 kg bags) from wholesale markets for the best rates.</div>
    </div>

    <div class="faq-item">
      <div class="faq-q">Can I run popcorn and cotton candy machines on an inverter or generator?</div>
      <div class="faq-a">Yes, but you need to match the power capacity. A small popcorn machine (800–1200W) can run on a 1.5 kVA inverter or generator. A large commercial machine (1500–2500W) needs at least a 3 kVA generator. Cotton candy machines draw 500–1500W depending on size. For gas models, you only need minimal electricity for the motor (100–200W), making them easy to run on any small inverter. Always use a stabiliser to protect the machine from voltage fluctuations, which are common at outdoor event locations.</div>
    </div>

